}) {
  private game!: GameManager;

  init() {
    /* one-time setup; runs once on register */
  }

  // Inject app collaborators with a setter — the ENGINE constructs the system,
  // so you cannot pass them through a constructor.
  setRefs(refs: { game: GameManager }) {
    this.game = refs.game;
  }

  // The per-frame tick. Name MUST be `update`. Args are in SECONDS, not ms.
  update(delta: number, time: number) {
    this.game.update(delta);
    this.queries.balls.entities.forEach((e) => {
      /* ... */
    });
    if (this.input.keyboard.getKeyDown('Space')) {
      /* ... */
    }
  }
}

world.registerSystem(GameLoopSystem); // register the CLASS, not an instance
const loop = world.getSystem(GameLoopSystem)!; // typed instance back
loop.setRefs({ game });
```

Inside a system, world resources are already on `this`: `this.world`, `this.scene`, `this.camera`, `this.renderer`, `this.input`, `this.player`, `this.playerEntity`, `this.queries`, `this.config`.

**These do NOT exist — a TS error here is a real bug, never "a known IWSDK typing issue." Do not cast `world` to `any` to silence it:**

| Guessed (wrong)                                                | Reality                                                                                                                                                  |
| -------------------------------------------------------------- | -------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------------- |
| `world.onUpdate(fn)` / `world.onFrame`                         | No such method. `World.update(delta,time)` is the engine tick the runtime calls for you — do not call, assign, or wrap it.                               |
| `world.ecs.registerSystem(...)`                                | No `world.ecs`. `(world as any).ecs?.registerSystem?.(...)` silently no-ops and ships a dead loop.                                                       |
| `world.createSystem({...})`                                    | No such method (returns `undefined`). `createSystem(...)` is the imported factory used as a base class.                                                  |
| `class { execute(dt) {} }`                                     | The tick method is `update(delta,time)`, not `execute`.                                                                                                  |
| `renderer.setAnimationLoop(...)` / raw `requestAnimationFrame` | The managed loop already ticks registered systems; a manual rAF does **not** run on the XR session loop, so the game won't tick in an immersive session. |

`requestAnimationFrame`/`setTimeout` are fine for pure DOM/CSS overlays (HTML fades) outside the 3D scene — but anything touching scene state, physics, scoring, or input must run in a System. The generated starter models this: see `src/index.template.ts` (`world.registerSystem(PanelSystem).registerSystem(RobotSystem)`) and `src/robot.ts` (a `createSystem` with `update()`).

**Don't let `as any` hide a broken game loop.** A "build passes, screenshot renders" app can still have a dead loop — the classic failure is guessing an engine path, casting it away, and swallowing the error into a silent rAF fallback:

```ts
// BAD — guesses a non-existent path, then silently runs a raw rAF loop
try {
  (world as any).ecs?.registerSystem?.(UpdateSystem);
} catch {
  requestAnimationFrame(rafLoop);
}
```

The correct call is `world.registerSystem(GameLoopSystem)`. Don't wrap engine calls in `try/catch` that swallows and falls back; let them throw. After `dev up`, confirm with `npx iwsdk ecs systems` that your systems are listed — if absent, the loop is running off-ECS (see `cli-reference.md`). The ECS debug tools (`pause`/`step`/`snapshot`) only see registered Systems; a hand-rolled rAF loop is invisible to them and keeps advancing even when ECS is "paused."

## ECS-Native Player Rig

```typescript
world.playerEntity; // Entity wrapping XROrigin Group
world.playerHeadEntity; // Entity for head space
world.playerSpaceEntities; // { head, raySpaces, gripSpaces, indexTipSpaces }

// Attach a HUD to the player's head
const hud = world.createTransformEntity(hudMesh, {
  parent: world.playerHeadEntity,
  persistent: true,
});
```

`createTransformEntity` returns an `Entity` whose `.object3D` is **optional** (`Object3D | undefined`). It always sets `object3D` (it falls back to `new Object3D()` when you pass nothing), so immediately after creation you can assert (`entity.object3D!.position`); inside systems/queries where an entity may have been torn down, guard instead (`if (!entity.object3D) continue;` or `entity.object3D?.position`). Do not blanket-cast to `any`.

//   Dynamic = gravity+forces, Kinematic = you move it, it pushes others.

// 2. Launch a projectile: one-shot impulse OR exact velocity
//    (PhysicsManipulation auto-removes after 1 frame).
entity.addComponent(PhysicsManipulation, { force: [0, 8, -3] }); // impulse at center of mass
entity.addComponent(PhysicsManipulation, { linearVelocity: [5, 0, 0] }); // overrides velocity

// 3. Read back: the system writes the simulated pose into object3D every frame.
const p = entity.object3D!.position; // updated by PhysicsSystem
const vel = entity.getVectorView(PhysicsBody, '_linearVelocity'); // live velocity (Float32Array xyz)
```

Tuning lives on `PhysicsBody`: `linearDamping` / `angularDamping` (drag),
`gravityFactor` (0 = float, >1 = heavy). Reach for Havok when there are collisions,
restitution, stacking, throwing, or rolling. Hand-roll a kinematic update ONLY for
strictly 1-axis/2D motion with no collision response (a slider, a spinning dial) —
do not write a substep-Euler integrator with manual `vel.y += GRAVITY*dt` and
`vel *= -0.6` bounces; that is exactly what the three components above give you,
deterministically. Canonical example: `examples/physics/src/index.ts`.

> If you genuinely need fully custom motion, scaffold `--no-physics` so you don't
> ship a disabled engine (the Havok WASM still bundles into `dist`). Do not enable
> physics and then hand-roll an integrator, and do not disable physics while
> reimplementing gravity by hand.

